# Git Discipline

## When to Commit

Commit only after the user has explicitly approved the result of an iteration.
Do not commit work-in-progress or unapproved changes.

## Conventional Commits Format

```
<type>[optional scope]: <short description>
```

| Type | Use for |
|------|---------|
| `feat` | New feature or functionality |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `chore` | Tooling, config, dependencies, project setup |
| `docs` | Documentation, README, rules updates |
| `refactor` | Code restructuring without behavior change |
| `test` | Adding or fixing tests |

## Examples

```
feat(calculator): add gross margin field
fix(sales-form): correct currency rounding on blur
chore: init project structure
docs: update rules — null input edge case
refactor(api): extract validation middleware
test(calculator): add unit tests for P&L logic
```

## Scope

Scope is optional but encouraged for feature-level changes. Use the tool or module name as scope.
